  "prompt": "I would like to know about the common prefixes namely iso- and neo- which are used in organic nomenclature. I just wanted explanations about using these, I mean when and where to use these and what do these mean?",
  "response": "Let me explain the prefixes iso- and neo- in organic nomenclature:\n\nISO- PREFIX:\n1. Meaning: \"Equal\" or \"similar\"\n2. Used primarily for branched alkanes and other compounds\n3. Indicates a specific type of branching pattern\n4. Typically used when there's a methyl group branching from the second-to-last carbon\n5. Examples:\n   - Isobutane (2-methylpropane)\n   - Isopentane (2-methylbutane)\n   - Isopropyl group (1-methylethyl group)\n\nNEO- PREFIX:\n1. Meaning: \"New\" or \"recent\"\n2. Used for specific types of branched compounds\n3. Indicates a more complex branching pattern\n4. Typically used when there are two methyl groups on the second-to-last carbon\n5. Examples:\n   - Neopentane (2,2-dimethylpropane)\n   - Neohexane (2,2-dimethylbutane)\n\nKey Differences:\n- Iso- involves one methyl branch\n- Neo- involves two methyl branches on the same carbon\n\nThese prefixes help simplify the naming of branched organic compounds.",
